Germany is the first in Europe to introduce "undefined sex" when registering children
Germany will be the first country in Europe to be allowed when registering children born by hermaphrodites, instead of male or female, to indicate "uncertain."
The parents of the child will have the right to leave the column "sex" for a time in the birth certificate of the unfilled.
Instead of "F" (female sex) or "M" (male sex), parents can temporarily record "X" (uncertain).
This decision is aimed at not pushing parents to rush with the operation to "clarify" the sex.
According to statistics, one in 2,000 newborns in the world are born a hermaphrodite.
