Scientists have shed light on how the dog's tail movements are associated with her mood.
Earlier studies have shown that satisfied dogs wag their tail to the right side (from the dog's point of view), while anxious dogs wave their tail predominantly on the left side.
But now scientists say that other members of the dog family can notice these subtle differences in tailwring and respond to them.
Professor Giorgio Wallworthigra, a neuroscientist at the University of Trent, says: "It is well known that people have the left and right sides of the brain differently involved in the formation of ductuators that cause positive or negative emotions.
Here we tried to look at this in other species.
He added that, just like a human, dogs have the right part of the brain controlling the left side of the body and vice versa, and the two hemispheres play different roles in emotions.
To learn more about how dogs react to the versatile tailings of other dogs, researchers observed the animals when they watched movies about other dogs.
They measured the heart rate of animals and analyzed their behavior.
We'll probably soon understand why their tails sometimes head to one side and sometimes to the other.
Professor Wallworthigara said: "We showed the dogs videos of dogs - either naturalistic versions or silhouette to get rid of any other distorting factors, and we could manipulate the tail movement and direct the tail more to the left or right.
When the animals saw that otherwise, an unspeaking dog moved the tail to the right (from the point of view of the dog's wagging tail), they remained completely relaxed.
But when they noticed that the tail was inclined mainly to the left (again from the point of view of the dog wagging tail), their heartbeat increased and they looked alarmed.
Professor Wallworthiara said he did not think that the dogs intentionally communicated with each other through these movements.
In fact, he believes that the dogs learned from their experience, what movements they should worry about, and which ones should not.
If there are several encounters with other dogs and often wagged their tail in one direction is associated with more friendly behavior, and the right side gives less friendly behavior, the dog reacts on the basis of this experience.
The researchers say these results could give owners, veterinarians, and trainers a deeper understanding of their animal's emotions.
Dog Behavior expert John Bradshaw, a visiting fellow at the University of Bristol Veterinary School, said it was not the first study to test whether the left and right sides mattered.
Last year, a group of scientists from Lincoln University found that dogs turn their heads to the left if they looked at an aggressive dog, and to the right if they look at a happy dog.
And in another scientific work of the University of Victoria in Canada, he reported: "Dogs were more likely to approach the robot dog, when the wagging of her tail was directed to the left, and not to the right, instead of becoming alarmed, the opposite behavior towards the Italian study.
He said the differences could have been due to the fact that dogs in various studies did not fully perceive animals in films or robot dogs as dogs.
It could be helpful to explore how dogs react to real dogs, he explained.
While there is sufficient evidence in different mammals that the two hemispheres of the brain are used for different purposes, many details are yet to be clarified, and the dogs are no exception.
However, given the ease with which their behavior can be reported, we'll probably soon understand why their tails are sometimes directed in one direction, and sometimes in the other.
