Russia Outside the fight for pollution of cities by cars
Attempts to solve the transport problems of large cities have been observed in most of the world's megacities since the second half of the twentieth century.
As a rule, it was about their reorganization and expansion of highways, or attempts to reduce the demand for car trips, the number of cars and the time of their use.
The example of Singapore is widely known, where a strict quota of the increase in the number of private cars has been introduced, and the right to purchase them at auctions.
Its price can be two to three times the price of the car itself.
European cities, including London, have imposed a fee for entering the city center.
In Germany, for example, in Hamburg and Stuttgart, so-called green zones are introduced, where only cars with a certain eco-class are allowed to enter, using also high-quality fuel (including biofuels or electric cars).
The Beijing Environmental Protection Agency, for example, approved in 2012 the "five-year clean air plan" with a total cost of about 250 billion yuan (about $40 billion).
According to Li Kunseng, director of transport pollution control at Beijing's Municipal Environmental Protection Office, the main goal of the five-year plan is to reduce the leading air pollutants by 20-35% by 2017, an increase in the number of private cars to a level not exceeding 6 million (now 5.2 million), as well as an increase of no more than 5% in fuel use per vehicle.
According to the agency, now vehicles in Beijing are responsible for 22.5% of total air pollution.
Among the main measures of the program is the restriction of the use of road transport, as well as the introduction of additional taxes for car owners.
Among other things, the urban measures of the "green five-year plan" include the accelerated transition to European fuel standards compared to the rest of the country, the introduction of a local system of eco-standards and marking of cars and fuel, restriction on the entry of cars in the central part of the city, a ban on the use of obsolete vehicles (in addition, the creation of incentive financial programs to replace old cars with hybrid or electric vehicles), the development of electric vehicles (including public and high-speed).
Among the automotive innovations of Beijing is also a ban on all private cars to move within the fifth transport ring (only in the capital of China six) one day a week (there is the relevant information contained in the license plate of the vehicle), as well as the issuance of registration plates for cars based on the lottery (for example, in 2011, the first year of the lottery, the total number of permits for the registration of private cars in Beijing was only one third of the number of 2010).
According to the current state program "Environmental protection for 2012-2020," the number of cities with high and very high air pollution should be reduced to 128 (in 2012 there were 138).
According to the Ministry of Natural Resources, in 2011 the "movable sources" accounted for 41% of all emissions of pollutants into the atmosphere of cities.
In Moscow, for example, emissions from cars are ten times higher than industrial, and in St. Petersburg - nine times.
In Russia, they are only beginning to think about the possibility of restrictive regulation of cars on the streets of cities.
Mikhail Blinkin, Director of the HSE Institute for Transport Economics and Transport Policy, believes that administrative and fiscal measures aimed at suppressing the demand for car travel are obviously unpopular, they can be taken by society only if they are fully universalized.
In the case of Moscow, there is a unique problem associated with the structure of its fleet, where there are two clusters of poorly sensitive to any regulatory impact - service and personal cars, as well as "privileged" users, the total number of which is at least 200 thousand. (about 5% of the total number of Moscow's fleet).
Recently, urbanists from the center of ECOM in St. Petersburg prepared a study where the balance of urban areas between residential buildings, the area of the road surface and the number of vehicles is analyzed.
The main findings of the researchers: the city center is provided with roads half the required, and most motorists living in the center do not use cars every day, leaving them for a long time in parking lots or just on the streets.
As a result, it is proposed to build not parking, but storages of cars, not to expand, but to reduce the roadway (so that the streets become more friendly for pedestrians), as well as limit the use and placement of personal transport within the boundaries of the territory of the security zone of the historical center (common area of about 3212 hectares, covering a number of central districts of the city).
The price of fuel will be led by a tax maneuver, which provides for an increase in the tax on the extraction of minerals (MET) on oil simultaneously with a decrease in export duties and an increase in excise duties.
