Goldman Sachs warns of risks to Russian economy
Goldman Sachs has warned of growing risks for Russia's main driver of fragile economic growth - consumption.
This is primarily a crisis of non-payments on unsecured consumer loans and mass reductions in workers.
Our main concern now is not that growth has slowed, but rather the structure of this growth.
Recently, it is completely driven by consumption, which almost does not reduce the turnover," said Clemens Grafe, chief economist at Goldman Sachs for Russia, presenting yesterday the quarterly report of the investment bank on the Russian economy.
Now the nominal increase in wages in Russia is about 10%.
With inflation of 6%, it will be able to provide future consumer demand at about the current level, expect in Goldman Sachs.
But the profitability of Russian companies is falling, so, most likely, they will be engaged in optimizing the costs of personnel.
Today we see a significant increase in the share of wages in GDP: if wages are growing by 10%, then GDP - only 2%, - said Mr. Grafe.
The companies faced a reduction in profitability.
If it doesn't grow, it can lead to dismissals and increased unemployment.
It is impossible not to raise the salaries of Russian business, commented the chief economist of Barclays Capital in Russia and the CIS Vladimir Pantyushin.
Unemployment near historical lows, competition for workers is high.
To lure employees from the outside or retain the current, employers have to raise salaries.
Consumption in Russia is supported and very rapid growth of demand.
According to Mr. Grafe, due to the extremely high rates on consumer loans, this type of lending does not have a multiplicative effect on the country's economy.
"We did not see the benefits for the economy from the growth of demand, the money does not diverge on the economy, but returns to the same banks in the form of interest payments," the economist said.
But the problem is different - Goldman Sachs expect an increase in delays in unsecured loans.
They are taken mainly by poor people who have nothing to provide.
Interest on such loans is high.
As a result, they are not returned more often," Mr. Grafe said.
Therefore, the second threat to the growth of the economy in Russia is a possible crisis of non-payments on unsecured loans.
Director of the HSE Banking Institute Vasily Solodkov is already seeing signs of a brewing banking crisis.
Small credit institutions, without access to the cheap resources that state banks have, were forced to raise funds from the population at high interest rates.
In response, state banks came on the path of war and began to reduce credit rates, - continues the economist.
Small credit institutions cannot issue loans at the same interest, otherwise they will have a negative interest margin.
If state banks do not abandon dumping, Russia is in danger of a full-fledged banking crisis, believes Vasily Solodkov.
Deprivation of licenses of a number of banks in recent weeks, the economist considers the harbinger of mass collapse.
"The state banks themselves will not cope with such a situation: the deposit insurance system was not originally designed for a systemic crisis," the head of the institute warns.
But the growth of consumption will slow down without a crisis of non-payment, believe in the investment bank, - because of the refusal to index the salaries of civil servants and the military, laid down in the current version of the draft budget.
Part of the impact on consumption will be mitigated by the freezing of the tariffs of natural monopolies (and, as a result, a decrease in inflation).
But only partially: if the investment does not grow (and there are no prerequisites for this yet - see the increase in consumption will still slow down, confident in Goldman Sachs.
Vladimir Pantyushin from Barclays Capital does not yet see the prerequisites for the implementation of pessimistic scenarios.
"The main risk is the fall in the price of oil," he says.
According to him, the Russian economy will begin to shrink at the cost of oil below $ 90 per barrel.
Goldman Sachs also noted that the Central Bank is not yet able to reduce interest rates in the economy.
There is a paradoxical picture: inflation has decreased, and banks began to raise rates.
