New antinicotine vaccine could deprive the process of smoking pleasure
Scientists have developed an anti-nicotine vaccine that could deprive the process of smoking cigarette pleasure.
One dose of the vaccine was able to protect mice from nicotine addiction for life.
Further tests are needed before the human trials, which will take several years, but Professor Ronald Crystal of Weil Cornell Medical College in New York said the first results are encouraging.
"We very much hope that such a vaccine strategy can finally help the millions of smokers who have tried to quit by trying to try all the methods on the market today, but found that their nicotine addiction is strong enough to overcome it with these modern means, Professor Cornell said.
The new vaccine contains a harmless virus that has been developed to carry genetic information for the production of antinicotine antibodies.
The virus selectively infects the liver cells, which then begin to produce a stable flow of antibodies.
Antibodies track track any nicotine molecules in the blood, neutralizing them before they reach the brain, preventing the smoker from getting nicotine.
In the tests, vaccinated mice, which were subsequently given nicotine, continued their normal activities.
And the mice that were not given the vaccine were relaxed, and this is a sign that nicotine reached their brains, the researchers say.
These experiments are described in the journal Science Translational Medicine.
Previous tobacco vaccines have failed because they contained antibodies.
To maintain a high level of antibodies, injections had to be done so often that they turned out to be expensive and impractical.
But the cost of the new vaccine is likely to be much lower because it turns liver cells into antibody factories.
Professor Crystal said that if the future human vaccine was completely safe, it could be given to children before they have a desire to try a cigarette, preventing nicotine addiction.
But it's more likely that it will be used by smokers to quit smoking.
They will know that if they start smoking again, they won't get this pleasure because of the nicotine vaccine, and it can help them get rid of this habit," he said.
