Agency "Rosbalt" deprived of the status of the media for the obscenity
On October 31, the Moscow City Court decided to invalidate the license for the registration of the agency "Rosbalt," - writes "Lenta."
Roskomnadzor insisted on the deprivation of the agency's status - for systematic and gross violations of the law on the media.
During the trial, an unpleasant precedent was created: the court considered it possible to close the media, in fact refusing to the publication the right to put forward counterarguments.
What is "Rosbalt"
CJSC "Rosbalt Information Agency" was established in St. Petersburg in 2000.
In the following years, the agency opened a second head office in Moscow and a number of regional units.
The agency also has offices in the countries of the former USSR.
Since 2001, Rosbalt has developed and functioned as a federal information and analytical agency.
By the mid-2000s, the agency was on the list of the most recognizable private online media in Russia.
At the same time, "Rosbalt" has always occupied a rather specific niche: the core of the exclusive publications of the agency was (and make up to date) notes with reference to sources in law enforcement agencies.
Talks about the proximity of the publication to the security structures continued throughout the existence of the agency.
Along with the fact that Rosbalt had an extensive database of sources in various departments, in favor of such assumptions, the fact that the project was headed by Natalia Chaplina - the wife of Viktor Cherkesov.
At the same time, Chaplina's role in the leadership of Rosbalt is not fully clear: it is often called the "head of the project."
The general director of the agency is Larisa Afonina, editor-in-chief - Nikolay Ulyanov.
Recently, "Rosbalt" did not appear in the ratings of the federal media - neither by citation nor by audience.
In October, the agency took the 25th place in the ranking of attendance of Russian media sites according to LiveInternet.
According to the same LiveInternet, the average daily audience of the site rosbalt.ru is about 150,000 unique visitors (and up to 500 thousand views), monthly - about three million unique visitors.
Among the most popular materials in the last five months are notes on the helplessness of the Kremlin in relations with Ukraine, the death of the soloist of the group "King and the jester," pogroms in the capital Biryulev.
The conflict between Rosbalt and Roskomnadzor began in July 2013, when amendments to the law on the media that banned journalists from seeking war, came into force.
The agency found a banned vocabulary in two videos published on the Agency's website ("Jigit from Krasnodar" and "Pussy Riot desecrated oil rigs").
The further sides describe differently.
Roskomnadzor, on the basis of the video materials, accused Rosbalt of gross and systematic violation of the law on the media and appealed to the court with a demand to remove the license from the Agency.
Rosbalt stated that the claims of the department are inappropriate: firstly, the videos were not editorial materials, secondly, the mother words in them were disguised, and, thirdly, immediately after the warning, the videos were removed from the site.
Representatives of the agency appealed Roskomnadzor's claims to the magistrate's court - and when the Moscow City Court accepted the claim of Roskomnadzor on October 22, 2013, the consideration of these complaints was still ongoing.
However, on the 25th of the magistrate, the judge made the decision not in favor of Rosbalt: the editor-in-chief Nikolai Ulyanov was found guilty of violating the code of administrative offenses and fined 20 thousand rubles - 10 thousand for each video.
Obviously, this predetermined the outcome of the hearing in the Moscow City Court - if you refuse to think that the outcome could be predetermined even earlier.
On October 31, the court decided to invalidate the certificate of registration of "Rosbalt," in fact depriving the agency of the status of the media.
It is impossible to say that "Rosbalt" in the course of this confrontation remained alone.
The Agency was supported by deputies of the state Duma (the statement to the head of Roskomnadzor Alexander Zharov was signed by 26 deputies on October 10; the document itself was filed at the initiative of the Communist Party).
The illegality of the closure of the publication was stated by the head of the Union of Journalists of Russia Vsevolod Bogdanov, Chairman of the Moscow Union of Journalists Pavel Gusev and the head of the presidential Council for human rights Mikhail Fedotov.
Moreover, according to Bogdanov, the leadership of Roskomnadzor even provided him with some guarantees that the revocation of the license will not come.
The trial of Rosbalt showed: under whose jurisdiction it is safer to be media in Russia today is a big question.
The gene of speech turned out to be a stimulator of the formation of synapses
Scientists from Johns Hopkins University and Mount Sinai School of Medicine have discovered a protein by which the "speech gene" Foxp2 performs its function, stimulating the formation of new connections between neurons.
The study is published in Science, on the website of the journal you can read its brief content.
The Foxp2 gene is the first known gene whose function is directly related to speech.
His role was established in 2001 thanks to the discovery of a family of several people who could not correctly pronounce the words and sometimes did not understand each other.
Scientists have found that family members were disrupted by the Foxp2 gene, but how it performs its function remained unknown.
In the new study, biologists have shown that at least part of their functions Foxp2 performs as a stimulator of the formation of new synapses in the brain region associated with the formation of speech.
It does this thanks to another gene, SRPX2.
The latter was found as a result of finding factors that stimulate the formation of synapses.
SRPX2 was one of the 10 similar genes found by the authors, while only Foxp2 creaks on its activity.
The fact that SRPX2 does affect vocalization, scientists confirmed in an experiment on mice.
When the animal's gene activity was artificially reduced, they screamed less when separated with the mother.
If the gene activity was restored, the frequency of the sounds produced was also restored.
Previously, mice also showed a link with the vocalization of Foxp2 itself.
Animals that were injected with a human copy of the gene were feeding more actively and at a lower frequency than normal mice.
So far, however, scientists do not know whether the work of Foxp2 and, accordingly, the SRPX2 managed by it is associated with purely "mechanical" properties of sound formation or more subtle processes.
