Syria and Russia insist that this is the work of the Syrian rebels.
The world community demanded from the Syrian leadership - in accordance with the agreement reached with the mediation of Russia - to destroy or bring to the non-working state all the capacity for the production of shells, poisonous gases and liquids and to fill the shells with these substances.
Now that this stage has been completed, the next step should be the destruction of the chemical weapons already in place by the Syrian army.
It is expected that this arsenal may have more than 1,000 tons of nerve agents, skin-drilled mustard gas and other banned chemicals stored in several dozen different places.
For its destruction, it is necessary that the OPCW and the Syrian authorities first agree on a schedule of actions - this is allotted for two weeks.
OPCW field chief Jerry Smith told the BBC that his inspectors "personally watched the destruction of the equipment."
"They now do not have the ability to further produce or mix chemical weapons," he said.
In a statement, the OPCW said that the inspectors visited 21 of the 23 facilities in Syria and were convinced that the plants for the production of shells and poisonous substances were either destroyed or put in disrepair.
The remaining two facilities are too dangerous to conduct an inspection there, the document says, but the equipment was transported and inspected by OPCW specialists.
