Why should an independent Scotland comply with Europe's orders?
Why change London's yoke on the yoke of Brussels, especially now?
Here are the real European news: the great post-war plan to unite Europe has finally stalled.
With the eurocrisis project "Europe" is officially dead.
Throughout the European Union, parties opposing the EU or canceling the euro as a single currency are gaining in force.
Even in Germany, the Euroskeptic party, the Alternative for Germany - founded this year only - emerged out of nowhere and received almost five million votes in the September federal election, thus essentially ousting the Free Democrats (similar to our Liberal Democrats) from the Bundestag.
There has always been an internal opposition to the plan to create a federal Europe.
However, the current economic crisis was a turning point.
The austerity measures imposed by Berlin and the European Central Bank, and the shackles imposed on national economies through the preservation of the single currency, led many people to believe that the project has gone too far.
The euro crisis is not much due to the fact that national governments work with excessive budget deficits - this was true only for Greece.
In fact, the Eurosystem has blocked its members at exchange rates favorable to German exporters - that German politicians want to keep.
Without the possibility of devaluation of the national currency, southern Europe is in a pre-disputable position in terms of production opportunities in comparison with Germany.
The only means of saving is to cut salaries and government spending, which is actively supported by Berlin.
Behind the current problems of the budget and currency is the deeper problem of Europe's productive abilities.
As a result of the set of green energy measures introduced by Brussels, the cipher, which means subsidizing French and German energy companies at the expense of the consumer, the European industry pays twice as much for electricity and four times as much for gas than in the United States.
It's paralyzingly unfavorable price conditions, as we've seen in Grangemouth.
No wage freeze in the world will stop the collapse of the cheap US shale gas victory over the European petrochemical industry.
As a result, a riot is brewing, especially in France, once the most ardent supporter of the EU.
After the war, the French political elite saw the EU as a way to control Germany and put Paris on the same level as Washington.
But Berlin no longer needs Paris as a means of obtaining political legitimacy, and has already imposed its own economic policies on Europe, leaving the devastated economy of France in distress.
The result is the right-wing, against the EU Marine Le Pen's party, the National Front, has just won the decisive additional elections, dropping the ruling party of socialists in third place.
The Front is now the most popular party in France, with 24 percent of the vote - a timely warning to British Labour that it is impossible to assume that the split among the right will automatically affect the left.
What makes Le Pen with his newfound popularity among the French working class?
It wants to use the EU elections next year to create a bloc in the European Parliament against the EU and against the single currency.
If - very likely - the parties opposed to the EU will receive support in these elections, such a bloc will be able to occupy a dominant position in the European Parliament for the first time.
Here's my opinion: the growing sentiment against the EU and against the single currency in Europe will merge together to destroy the euro.
The EU will not disappear, but it will again be something of a vague "Europe" (sovereign) nations that General de Gaulle liked.
Germany and several dependent economies can save the euro, but France and southern Europe will restore their own currencies.
I assume that the UK is distancing itself from this project, hoping to get closer to the United States.
However, Washington's growing interest in the Pacific indicates the likelihood that Britain will be ignored in the cold of the Atlantic.
In what position does it leave Scotland?
We can choose to become a region of Little England.
Or we can defend our own economic interests, which means, among other things, to send Berlin and Brussels to hell.
I suspect that Scotland will be able to succeed in a more free European arrangement, provided that we retain our currency.
Cooperation with other like-minded countries will be easier in non-federal Europe of nations.
Otherwise, we should consider repeating Norway's experience and preserving our economic independence.
The Scottish National Party's government is, oddly enough, the most successful political movement in Europe directed against austerity measures, which received an impressive majority in 2011 thanks to objections to spending cuts proposed (and realized) by Labour Treasury Chancellor Alistair Darling and the later coalition of Tories and the later-off coalition of Tories.
Scotland would now be ridiculous to vote for independence only to take austerity measures imposed by Berlin and Brussels.
