A former CNN correspondent, Pat Etheridge, is a journalist specializing in children's health and family issues.
Should a mother be scared if her daughter begins to form the rudiments of the mammary gland and grow pubic hair at 7 or 8 years?
At the annual conference of the American Academy of Pediatrics this week in Orlando, Florida, children's endocrinologist Dr. Paul Caplavitz explained that these early physical changes are quite common among American girls and represent a new norm.
"I spend a lot of time calming my parents - usually that doesn't mean the rapid onset of total puberty," said Kaplovitz.
Obvious signs of development, such as growing breasts, pubic and axillary hair and body odor, appear earlier in girls.
But there was only a slight shift in the age of menarche (the first menstruation) over the past four decades.
In the United States, the average age is 12.5 years and decreased from 12.75 in 1970.
"After breasts begin to develop, it takes at least two to three years before menarche," said Caplowvitz, who is also the author of the book "Early puberty in girls: how to cope with this common problem."
Time is the most accurate check on how puberty will progress.
A debate is ongoing on what constitutes the actual onset of puberty, but is considered "premature," when breast augmentation is accompanied by a sharp increase in growth to 8 years.
In most cases, the process will slow down or stop - this is something that the pediatrician can monitor carefully.
Faster progression may serve as the basis for endocrinologist tests to rule out serious problems such as tumors or cysts.
There are procedures to delay early menstruation and prevent another consequence: premature aging of the bones, which can eventually lead to slowing growth and low growth in adulthood.
Recommendations for drug or hormonal therapy are based on the age of the child, the level of development, the rate of growth and emotional maturity.
Psychosocial aspects are also important.
Caplowitz is cautious with the medications, but admits that "pulling puberty can alleviate the behavioral problems and feelings of girls that they are different from their peers.
Another big problem is clear: parents simply do not want their very young daughters to have menstrual periods.
"They're worried about the risk of pregnancy or even how they'll handle hygiene issues," said Caplavitz.
It was a shock, - recalls one woman whose daughter began menstruation at the age of 10.
Although there were signs and we talked about menstruation, it wasn't emotionally ready.
She came home from the school, frightened and frustrated by the fact that she was the first among her friends.
There are many advertised theories about the causes of early puberty.
However, there is no consistent evidence that hormones in milk or other foods, chemicals in the environment or sexual messages in the media are to blame.
In boys, like girls, puberty occurs earlier.
Caplowitz argues that the premise that has the most weight is an obesity epidemic.
In 2001, he helped conduct a study of girls from 6 to 9 years old, which links the amount of fat in the body to the timing of puberty.
Other data confirm this finding, but there are many other contributing factors.
In this country, African-American and Latin American girls tend to reach puberty before their white peers.
There are various explanations.
Around the world, early puberty appears to be affected by everything from economic conditions and climate to genes.
Another mystery: although boys have facial and pubic hair appear at a younger age, the tendency to full early puberty is not as pronounced as in girls.
Other doctors attending the AAP conference confirmed the complexity of the topic.
The appearance of acne and pubic hair is common even in infants and children of toddler age.
"We need to be careful about how we define the true onset of puberty," said Dr. Lawrence Silverman, a pediatric endocrinologist at the Goriyeb Children's Hospital in G. Morristown, New Jersey.
Parents should not be embarrassed to receive instructions from the pediatrician about how to talk to their child.
"This may mean an earlier-needed-expected conversation," - explained Caplavitz.
If you remain calm, your child will usually react well.
Girls who flourish early need confirmation that even when this happens before that, this process is a normal part of life.
