Syria has destroyed its chemical weapons manufacturing means, says the observation group
Syria destroyed the main equipment for the production of chemical weapons and ammunition with poison gas, an international observation group said on Thursday, while fierce clashes raged in the north of the country, near one of the sites where toxic substances are believed to be stored.
On Thursday, a Syrian group of activists said more than 120,000 people had been killed since the start of the country's civil war nearly three years ago.
The statement of the Organization on the prohibition of chemical weapons was made one day before
The deadline of 1 November, set by this Hague-based organization for Damascus to destroy or make all chemical weapons production facilities and mechanisms to mix chemicals to produce poison gas and fill it with ammunition.
Completing what is essentially the initial stage of destruction is an important milestone in an ambitious schedule that aims to destroy all of Damascus's chemical weapons by mid-2014.
The destruction of the equipment means that Syria can no longer produce new chemical weapons.
Nevertheless, Damascus has yet to begin the destruction of existing weapons and stockpiles.
The country is believed to have about 1,000 metric tons of chemicals and weapons, including mustard gas and nerve gas.
This statement was made during the fierce fighting on Thursday in the city of Safira, which, according to experts, is home to a chemical weapons production facility, as well as its storage sites, according to the Syrian Center for Human Rights, based in Britain.
A group of activists who tracked casualties through a network of activists in Syria said on Thursday that 120,296 people had been killed.
Of this number, it is said that 61,067 are civilians, including 6,365 children.
On the government's side, the group said, 29,954 people are members of President Bashar al-Assad's armed forces, 18,678 are pro-government fighters and 187 Lebanese fighters Hezbollah.
Also among the dead, as stated in the statement, were 2,202 military defectors and about 5375 opposition fighters, many of them foreigners.
According to the UN estimate of July 25, 100,000 have died in the conflict since March 2011.
This number has not been updated since then.
The conflict forced about 2 million people to flee the country.
Assad's troops fought rebels in Safire for weeks, many of whom are linked to al-Qaeda groups.
The center said there were casualties on Thursday on either side, but did not provide specific data.
The fighting underscored the danger faced by chemical weapons inspectors, driven by the tight deadlines of their mission to rid Syria of the toxic arsenal, in the midst of an ongoing civil war.
In a statement, the OPCW, which is working closely with the United Nations, said its team was now satisfied that it had tested and destroyed all critical means of production and equipment for mixing/refueling equipment.
She added that no additional inspection activities were currently planned.
Earlier this week, the inspectors said they had completed the first round of verification work, attending 21 of the 23 facilities claimed by Damascus.
They were unable to visit two places for security reasons, the inspectors said.
On Thursday, the OPCW said both places were, according to Syria's statement, aband and... The chemical weapons programme items in them have been moved to other declared locations that have been checked.
It was not possible to find out immediately whether the object in Safire was one of the two places that the OPCW inspectors could not visit.
Syria has unveiled a plan to completely destroy its chemical weapons, which is due to be approved next month by the OPCW Executive Committee.
"I welcome the courage and bravery that you have all demonstrated in the most difficult mission ever undertaken by this organization," said Ahmet Uzyumju, director general of the observation team, in a comment published by the OPCW.
For the third year, the civil war has confronted rebels, mostly Sunni Muslims, with the Assad government and his security forces, which are members of his Alawite sect, the dissent of Shia Islam.
As for other events, the center's head, Rami Abdurrahman, said there had been a strong explosion on Wednesday at an air defense facility in the coastal province of Latakia.
The cause of the explosion is unknown, he said.
